{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_36","type":"command_execution","command":"/usr/bin/bash -lc 'rg -n \"Generated LOC|test_generation_failed|dynamic-access|14/14|100.00|metrics status|failure|human-intervention\" -S .'","aggregated_output":"./skills/review-library-bulk-update/SKILL.md:92:- CI failures point to a real regression or invalid update.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:21:- Require at least 50% reported dynamic-access coverage when there are dynamic-access calls to cover. Use the exploded stats files under `stats/<group>/<artifact>/<metadata-version>/stats.json` when available, and block the PR when dynamic-access coverage is below 50% or the PR provides no credible dynamic-access coverage evidence for non-zero dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:22:- Treat dynamic-access coverage counts as a minimum gate, not complete metadata evidence. They can miss metadata required through downstream libraries, so do not use high coverage alone to prove that the submitted metadata is complete or necessary.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:23:- Treat `0/0` dynamic-access coverage as a valid no-calls case, not as failed coverage. Do not reject a PR only because the exploded stats report `0/0` dynamic-access calls while the PR adds metadata; those stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:59:   - Confirm reported dynamic-access coverage is at least 50% when the stats include dynamic-access calls.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:60:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls and `reachability-metadata.json` is `{}`, that is acceptable as long as the test is library-specific and the scope is otherwise correct.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:61:   - If the PR reports zero dynamic-access calls while adding metadata, do not reject it on that basis alone; dynamic-access stats can miss metadata required through downstream libraries.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:62:   - If the stats report less than 50% coverage for non-zero dynamic-access calls, or no usable coverage signal for claimed dynamic-access behavior, ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:84:  - Reported dynamic-access coverage is below 50% for non-zero dynamic-access calls, absent for claimed dynamic-access behavior, or not credible from the diff.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:94:- For insufficient dynamic-access coverage: say that new-library PRs need at least 50% dynamic-access coverage when there are dynamic-access calls to cover, and ask for stronger tests or refreshed coverage evidence.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:95:- For metadata/coverage mismatch: ask for investigation only when the PR makes concrete coverage claims that are not supported by the diff, or when reported dynamic-access coverage is below the 50% minimum for non-zero dynamic-access calls. Do not argue from metadata contents alone.\n./skills/fix-missing-reachability-metadata/SKILL.md:16:1. Reproduce the failure:\n./skills/fix-missing-reachability-metadata/SKILL.md:67:- If failures look unrelated or tooling looks inconsistent, verify both `JAVA_HOME` and `GRAALVM_HOME` point to a compatible GraalVM JDK distribution.\n./skills/README.md:27:It covers compile-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the compile fix, preserve meaningful tests, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:32:It covers native-image runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: verify the native path is fixed rather than skipped, keep metadata and test changes scoped, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-native-image-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes a native-image runtime failure for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the runtime/native fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair metadata or tests after an existing library version compiles and builds a native image, but the native image fails when the test runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library is already supported, so the goal is to restore native-image behavior for a newer version while preserving existing dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:18:- Do not accept fixes that hide the failing native path by skipping assertions, skipping native-image runtime execution, or weakening the test until the failure disappears.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:45:   - Confirm the metadata or test change matches the observed native runtime failure, such as missing reflection, resources, proxies, serialization constructors, JNI access, or class initialization behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:50:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:53:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:54:   - If metadata fixes make the native run pass but the dynamic-access ratio drops, ask for restored coverage first. Passing native execution is not enough by itself.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:61:   - Do not require an exact match. Small differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:62:   - Treat a large drop as blocking or at least requiring explanation when the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:68:   - If current-defaults and future-defaults lanes both run, both should pass unless the PR clearly targets only one failing lane and the other failure is unrelated infrastructure noise.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:75:- The PR is scoped to the target existing library and the native-image runtime failure it fixes.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:86:- Metadata additions are unrelated to the failure or affect other libraries without justification.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:87:- CI failures indicate the native-image runtime problem is not actually fixed.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:100:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/FixTestNativeImageRun.java:26: * Gradle task to fix test failures during native-image runs.\n./docs/CI.md:43:  - Uses: [`fetchExistingLibrariesWithNewerVersions`](../tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck-harness.gradle) plus [`generateNewLibraryVersionCompatibilityMatrix`](../tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck-harness.gradle) to build a [`ci.json`](../ci.json)-driven matrix. The matrix generator limits each library to at most 30 newer versions per run before expanding across the configured GraalVM JDK/OS combinations, records tested versions only after they pass on every required environment, and creates a single aggregated failure issue per failed library version while preserving the prior failure issue format with added OS and JDK lines.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-javac-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes Java compilation failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the compile fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:44:   - Confirm the edit addresses the actual Java compilation failure, such as renamed classes, changed method signatures, module boundaries, annotation processors, or dependency coordinates.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:49:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:52:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - Do not require an exact match. Small differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:60:   - Treat a large drop as blocking or at least requiring explanation when the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:66:   - If current-defaults and future-defaults lanes both run, both should pass unless the PR clearly targets only one failing lane and the other failure is unrelated infrastructure noise.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:73:- The PR is scoped to the target existing library and the compile failure it fixes.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:85:- CI failures indicate the compile problem is not actually fixed.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:98:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./docs/DEVELOPING.md:216:Use this when a library's new version causes native-image run test failures. The task will:\n./docs/DEVELOPING.md:280:  Output: `metadata/<group>/<artifact>/<version>/test/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json`\n./build.gradle:341: * indicating success or failure.\n./build.gradle:402: * per-command logs under build/command-logs and aggregating failures.\n./build.gradle:422:    def failures = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<Map>())\n./build.gradle:431:                failures.add([label: label, logFile: logFile, exit: exit])\n./build.gradle:440:    if (!failures.isEmpty()) {\n./build.gradle:442:        failures.each { f ->\n./build.gradle:446:        failures.each { f ->\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/stats/LibraryStatsSchemaValidator.java:80:        List<String> failures = new ArrayList<>();\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/stats/LibraryStatsSchemaValidator.java:87:                            StatsLocation location = validateStatsPath(file, statsRoot, failures);\n./tests/tck-build-logic/src/m